{"title_page": "Whatever It Takes (Imagine Dragons song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name = Whatever It Takes\n| cover = Whatever It Takes Imagine Dragons.jpg\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Imagine Dragons]]\n| album = [[Evolve (Imagine Dragons album)|Evolve]]\n| B-side = \"[[Thunder (Imagine Dragons song)|Thunder]]\" (official remix)\n| released = {{start date|2017|5|8}}\n| format =\n* [[CD single]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n| length = {{duration|m=3|s=21}}\n| label =\n* [[Kidinakorner]]\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer =\n* [[Dan Reynolds (singer)|Dan Reynolds]]\n* [[Wayne Sermon]]\n* [[Ben McKee]]\n* [[Daniel Platzman]]\n* [[Joel Little]]\n| genre =*[[Pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/imagine-dragons-drop-new-single-whatever-it-takes-announce-third-album-evolve|title=Imagine Dragons Drop New Single \u201cWhatever It Takes\u201d & Announce Third Album \u2018Evolve\u2019|last=Mench|first=Chris|quote=the song features fast-paced verses, but otherwise sticks close to the formula of soaring pop-rock choruses.|date=May 9, 2018|website=Genius|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[arena rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-10-best-imagine-dragons-songs|title=The 10 best Imagine Dragons songs|last=Everley|first=Dave|quote=Modern R&B retooled for an arena rock audience|date=August 14, 2018|website=Louder Sound|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[pop-rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicalhype.com/track-review-imagine-dragons-whatever-takes/|title=Imagine Dragons, \u2018Whatever It Takes\u2019|date=May 16, 2017|quote=On the verses of \u201cWhatever It Takes,\u201d Dan Reynolds approaches the vocals highly rhythmically, in pop-rap fashion.|website=The Musical Hype|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n| producer = Joel Little\n| chronology = [[Imagine Dragons]]\n| prev_title = [[Thunder (Imagine Dragons song)|Thunder]]\n| prev_year = 2017\n| next_title = [[Next to Me (Imagine Dragons song)|Next to Me]]\n| next_year = 2018\n| misc = {{External music video|{{YouTube|gOsM-DYAEhY|\"Whatever It Takes\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Whatever It Takes'''\" is a song by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Imagine Dragons]]. The song was released on May 8, 2017, as a promotional single through [[Kidinakorner]] and [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]. It later became the third single from the band's third studio album, ''[[Evolve (Imagine Dragons album)|Evolve]]'', on October 6, 2017. It was also the official theme song for [[World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc.|WWE]]'s [[Pay-Per-View|PPV]] event [[Battleground (2017)|Battleground]], in addition to its inclusion in the video game ''[[Madden NFL 18]]''. The song was sent to US [[contemporary hit radio]] on February 13, 2018.\n\n==Background==\nThe song was announced alongside the name and album art of ''[[Evolve (Imagine Dragons album)|Evolve]]'' via Twitter on May 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Da'Shan Smith|date=May 9, 2017|title=Imagine Dragons Are Ready to 'Evolve' With Upcoming Album & Tour, Share New Song 'Whatever It Takes'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7791817/imagine-dragons-evolve-new-album-tour-whatever-it-takes|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, they performed the song on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/VIDEO-Imagine-Dragons-Performs-Whatever-It-Takes-on-LATE-NIGHT-20171031|title=Imagine Dragons Performs 'Whatever It Takes' on LATE NIGHT|work=Broadway World|date=October 31, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Imagine Dragons asked [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] to stop using \"Whatever It Takes\" on their conference website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kqradio.com/index.php/2018/02/16/imagine-dragons-asks-conservative-group-to-stop-using-whatever-it-takes/|title=Imagine Dragons asks conservative group to stop using \"Whatever It Takes\"|publisher=Q95|date=February 16, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wixx.com/news/articles/2018/feb/16/imagine-dragons-asks-conservative-group-to-stop-using-whatever-it-takes/|title=Imagine Dragons asks conservative group to stop using \"Whatever It Takes\"|publisher=WIXX 101|date=February 16, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2018, they performed the song live before game two of the [[2018 Stanley Cup Finals]] at [[T-Mobile Arena]] in their hometown of [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Imagine Dragons rock Cup Final before Game 2|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/imagine-dragons-perform-before-stanley-cup-final-game-2/c-298855920|publisher=NHL Enterprises, L.P.|website=NHL.com|date=May 30, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)'s [[Utah Jazz]] frequently play the song prior to tip-off of every home game at [[Vivint Smart Home Arena]] in [[Salt Lake City|Salt Lake City, Utah]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Walden|first=Eric|title=Utah Jazz sleepwalk past Cleveland Cavaliers, 115-99, for sixth straight victory|url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2019/01/19/live-jazz-take-cavs/|newspaper=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=January 19, 2019|access-date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nA music video for the song was released on October 12, 2017. It was directed by [[Matt Eastin]] and Aaron Hymes. Eastin had also previously directed the music videos for Imagine Dragons' songs \"[[On Top of the World (Imagine Dragons song)|On Top of the World]]\", \"[[Roots (Imagine Dragons song)|Roots]]\", and \"[[Believer (Imagine Dragons song)|Believer]]\". The video begins with lead singer [[Dan Reynolds (singer)|Dan Reynolds]] swimming through a room filled with water. It then cuts to a scene in which Reynolds and the band are playing in the same room; however, it is not filled with water in this scene. As they perform the chorus of the song, the roof crumbles and rain starts pouring in. Throughout the video, the rain persists and the room eventually fills completely with water. However, the band still plays. As Reynolds sings, objects such as boxing gloves and keys float by him along with two people who are seemingly sirens, tugging at him from both sides. Before the final chorus, the music stops and the band floats lifelessly on the water. When they break into song again, the stage has completely changed as the room is no longer underwater, but on fire as the band plays on it. As the video ends, everything is on fire and the music stops.<ref>{{cite news|date=October 12, 2017|title=Imagine Dragons - Whatever It Takes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gOsM-DYAEhY|work=[[YouTube]]|access-date=October 12, 2017}}</ref> The video won the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Rock Video]] award.\nIts official music video has received over 673 million views and 4 million likes as of March 2020\n\n==Critical reception==\n''[[The Guardian]]'' writes that \"Whatever It Takes\" was \"written with a sports highlights package in mind (\"I love the adrenaline in my veins\", wails frontman Dan Reynolds, before chart pop's current obligatory chorus of \"woah-ohs\" enters).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/22/imagine-dragons-evolve-review-lifeless-electronic-tinged-arena-rock|title=Imagine Dragons: Evolve review \u2013 lifeless electronic-tinged arena rock|magazine=[[The Guardian]]|last=Davies|first=Hannah J|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nAs of May 15, 2018, the song has peaked at number 12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"Hot100\"/><ref name=\"No.24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8252366/drake-gods-plan-hot-100-eighth-week-number-one|title=Drake's 'God's Plan' Tops Billboard Hot 100 for Eighth Week|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 19, 2018|accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track